question 2¶

An electrical manufacturing company conducts quality checks at specified periods on the products it manufactures. Historically, the failure rate for the manufactured item is 5%. Suppose a random sample of 10 manufactured items is selected. Answer the following questions.

2.1 Probability that none of the items are defective?

0.59873

2.2 Probability that exactly one of the items is defective?

0.3151

2.3 Probability that two or fewer of the items are defective?

0.07463

2.4 Probability that three or more of the items are defective ?

0.01047

Question 4¶

Accuracy in understanding orders for a speech based bot at a restaurant is important for the Company X which has designed, marketed and launched the product for a contactless delivery due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Recognition accuracy that measures the percentage of orders that are taken correctly is 86.8%. Suppose that you place order with the bot and two friends of yours independently place orders with the same bot. Answer the following questions

4.1 What is the probability that all three orders will be recognised correctly?.

0.6539

4.2 What is the probability that none of the three orders will be recognised correctly?

0.002299

4.3 What is the probability that at least two of the three orders will be recognised correctly?

0.95225

Question 5¶

A group of 300 professionals sat for a competitive exam. The results show the information of marks obtained by them have a mean of 60 and a standard deviation of 12. The pattern of marks follows a normal distribution. Answer the following questions

5.1 What is the percentage of students who score more than 80?

In [2]:
z=(80-60)/12
z

cu_dis = stats.norm.cdf(z)
a = (1-cu_dis) * 300
a
Out[2]:
14.33710568184441

5.2 What is the percentage of students who score less than 50?

In [3]:
z=(50-60)/12
z

cu_dis = stats.norm.cdf(z)
cu_dis
a = cu_dis * 300
a
Out[3]:
60.69851428909293

Explain 1 real life industry scenario [other than the ones mentioned above] where you can use the concepts learnt in this module of Applied statistics to get a data driven business solution

Weather forecasting - in weather forcasting data is collected about temperature , wind speed humidity and these previously known data can be used to predict the weather of the upcoming days. Weather forcasting is very helpful in many domain , it may be used in agriculture as in when to sow seed . it may be used by logistics company to find the apt situation or day to transfer goods etc.

E-commerce companies also rely upon statistics to know maybe which is best overall selling product in a city , which product sale brings maximum profit etc . With the help os stats they can may be restock the item which is selling fast

Funds_M = []
count = 1
for ele in company_df['Funding']:
    
    if "K" in ele:
        temp_k = float(ele[1:-1])*1000
        ele = temp_k / 1000000
        Funds_M.append(ele)
        count = count + 1
    elif "M" in ele:
        temp_m = float(ele[1:-1])
        ele = temp_m
        Funds_M.append(ele)
        count = count + 1
    elif "B" in ele:
        temp_b = float(ele[1:-1])*1000
        ele = temp_b
        Funds_M.append(ele)
        count = count + 1

Statistical analysis

Is there any significant difference between Funds raised by companies that are still operating vs companies that closed down? Write the null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis. Test for significance and conclusion

H0 = There is no significant difference between funds raised by operating and closed comapnies
Ha = There is significant difference between funds raised by operating and closed comapnies

There is no specific level of significance mention, so we consider the default 0.05 - 5%
